<br>
There are three basic subtypes of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> sapiens</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> species, alphabetically: Caucasoid, Mongoloid, Negroid. There are countless variations on the above three themes, and thousands of sub-subtypes. Each of these three subtypes has a basic genetic template which shows up in its hair formation, skin pigmentation, and bone and muscle structure. <br>
<br>
It is rather easy for a forensics expert to identify the race of a suspect by a strand of hair, and even tell what part of the body it came from. Are they guessing? No. Differences in how the strand of hair was assembled in the follicle can tell what ethnic group the suspect is.<br>
<br>
Does this mean that one subtype is better than another? No. <br>
Does this mean that one subtype is more advanced? No.<br>
Does this mean that one subtype should be 'saved'? No.<br>
<br>
This is where science ends and people, with all their hangups and prejudices, step in. &quot;Oh, look! There are basic universal differences between the human races, much akin to the subspecies of dogs! Since I think St. Bernards are the best kind of dog, all other dogs must be genetically inferior!&quot;<br>
<br>
Bah.<br>
<br>
Again, science doesn't care what you do with the information, so long as the information is correct. Don't accuse faulty researchers of faulty research. <p><BR><CENTER><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=3579"><IMG SRC=http://personal.jax.bellsouth.net/jax/f/j/fjferry/img/ezb-euphemism-sig.jpg ALT="Adastra's Personal Signature" BORDER=0></A></CENTER><BR><CENTER>Corruptor of the Fifteenth Soul</CENTER></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ubjarkibearskin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjarki Bearskin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(12/20/01 6:23:09 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Ethnology&quot;</span><hr size=1> Careful, there, Adastra, I was called a racist for even mentioning those three words, and told to go hang out with the rest of my KKK buddies.  But then again, the same person in another post said that intermingling of races has weakened the &quot;hearth spirit&quot;.  Hmmm......<br>
